Terraform EC2 Instance with Root Volume Configuration

This repository demonstrates how to launch an **AWS EC2 instance** using Terraform, while configuring the root block device (volume size and type) dynamically through a single object variable.

---

## 📂 Files

### `variables.tf`
```hcl
# Define a single object variable to hold EC2 instance details
variable "insta_details" {
  type = object({
    vol_siz    = number   # Root volume size in GB
    vol_typ    = string   # Root volume type (e.g., gp3, gp2, io1)
    insta_deta = string   # EC2 instance type (e.g., t3.micro, t2.small)
  })

  # Default values (can be overridden at runtime)
  default = {
    vol_siz   = 10        # Default root volume size
    vol_typ   = "gp3"     # Default root volume type
    insta_deta = "t3.micro" # Default EC2 instance type
  }
}
```

---

### `data.tf`
```hcl
# Find the latest Ubuntu 22.04 AMI published by Canonical
data "aws_ami" "own_ami_ubuntu_IND" {
  most_recent = true
  owners      = ["099720109477"] # Canonical's AWS account ID

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-jammy-22.04-amd64-server-*"]
  }

  filter {
    name   = "virtualization-type"
    values = ["hvm"]
  }
}
```

---

### `res.tf`
```hcl
# Create an EC2 instance using the AMI and variable configuration
resource "aws_instance" "compute" {
  ami           = data.aws_ami.own_ami_ubuntu_IND.id
  instance_type = var.insta_details.insta_deta  # Instance type from variable

  root_block_device {
    delete_on_termination = true
    volume_size           = var.insta_details.vol_siz  # Volume size from variable
    volume_type           = var.insta_details.vol_typ  # Volume type from variable
  }
}

